WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.020
In the last module, you learned how to open
a call and run the basic fact find.

2
00:00:05.580 --> 00:00:08.780
Now we're going a level deeper into
discovery.

3
00:00:09.260 --> 00:00:13.340
So stick with me here because this is where
the real skill shows up.

4
00:00:14.420 --> 00:00:19.580
Let me draw a clear line between qualification
and discovery because they are not the

5
00:00:19.580 --> 00:00:25.020
same thing. Qualification is basically
asking, can we do business with this person?

6
00:00:25.420 --> 00:00:26.780
Do they own the property?

7
00:00:27.100 --> 00:00:29.780
Is it residential? Is it in our market?

8
00:00:29.780 --> 00:00:31.940
Is there some reason they want to sell?

9
00:00:32.580 --> 00:00:36.220
Those are the basics and you covered a lot
of that in the fact find.

10
00:00:37.720 --> 00:00:40.600
Discovery is a completely different
question.

11
00:00:41.020 --> 00:00:45.600
Discovery is asking, why should we do
business with this person right now?

12
00:00:45.920 --> 00:00:48.520
What's really going on underneath the
surface?

13
00:00:48.940 --> 00:00:50.420
What's the actual pain?

14
00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:53.280
What happens if nothing changes in their
situation?

15
00:00:53.800 --> 00:00:55.000
How urgent is this?

16
00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:57.600
Qualification confirms the basics.

17
00:00:58.100 --> 00:01:00.200
Discovery uncovers the real motivation.

18
00:01:00.920 --> 00:01:04.460
Both matter, but discovery is where deals
are actually made.

19
00:01:04.760 --> 00:01:10.120
You can qualify someone all day long, but if
you don't understand what's really driving

20
00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:12.380
them, you're just collecting data.

21
00:01:13.360 --> 00:01:19.200
So you've already established rapport, you've
asked the qualification questions, you've

22
00:01:19.200 --> 00:01:22.020
confirmed the basics. Now you go deeper.

23
00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:25.540
And the first place to go is the real
motivation.

24
00:01:25.540 --> 00:01:27.380
Here's the thing about sellers.

25
00:01:28.260 --> 00:01:32.720
Most of them won't tell you the real reason
they're selling on the first answer.

26
00:01:33.340 --> 00:01:37.460
They just won't. They'll give you the
surface level version.

27
00:01:37.900 --> 00:01:39.760
I just want to see what it's worth.

28
00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:43.060
Or I'm thinking about downsizing.

29
00:01:43.740 --> 00:01:45.220
That's the polished answer.

30
00:01:45.800 --> 00:01:49.920
The real story is usually something messier
and more human than that.

31
00:01:50.780 --> 00:01:53.220
Your job is to go underneath.

32
00:01:53.740 --> 00:01:59.920
And the way you do it is by asking why in
different ways without sounding like a five

33
00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:03.860
year old. You might say, you mentioned
you're thinking about selling.

34
00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:07.880
What's driving that? Or how long has this
been on your mind?

35
00:02:08.300 --> 00:02:11.660
Or what changed that made you start thinking
about it now?

36
00:02:11.800 --> 00:02:15.220
Or what would it mean for you to have this
handled?

37
00:02:15.220 --> 00:02:19.680
Each one of those follow up questions peels
back another layer.

38
00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:21.780
Don't accept the first answer.

39
00:02:22.340 --> 00:02:25.000
Keep digging, gently but persistently.

40
00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:27.520
People want to tell you what's going on.

41
00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:29.940
They just need to feel safe enough to do it.

42
00:02:30.920 --> 00:02:34.240
The next area to explore is financial
burden.

43
00:02:34.720 --> 00:02:36.160
And this is a big one.

44
00:02:36.600 --> 00:02:40.600
Financial pressure is one of the strongest
motivators out there.

45
00:02:40.640 --> 00:02:43.100
But people are often embarrassed about it.

46
00:02:43.100 --> 00:02:45.940
So you have to create safety around the
topic.

47
00:02:45.940 --> 00:02:50.400
You might ask something like, is the property
costing you anything to hold on to right

48
00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:54.840
now? Like mortgage, taxes, insurance,
maintenance?

49
00:02:55.360 --> 00:02:58.540
Or are there any payments you've fallen
behind on?

50
00:02:58.540 --> 00:03:04.760
Or if you don't mind me asking, do you have
a rough idea of what's owed on the property?

51
00:03:05.160 --> 00:03:11.420
If they reveal financial strain, if they're
behind on payments, if there are tax liens,

52
00:03:11.420 --> 00:03:13.560
if there's a foreclosure looming?

53
00:03:13.720 --> 00:03:16.900
That is critical information for the
acquisition team.

54
00:03:17.220 --> 00:03:19.420
That changes the entire picture.

55
00:03:20.540 --> 00:03:22.140
There's one more question.

56
00:03:22.700 --> 00:03:25.740
And it's so important I want to call it out
on its own.

57
00:03:26.160 --> 00:03:29.640
The what if question. What happens if you
don't sell?

58
00:03:30.180 --> 00:03:32.840
What does that look like six months from
now?

59
00:03:33.200 --> 00:03:37.100
This question forces them to confront the
consequences of doing nothing.

60
00:03:37.720 --> 00:03:41.700
And their answer tells you everything you
need to know about urgency.

61
00:03:41.700 --> 00:03:45.720
If they say something like, I just keep
renting it out.

62
00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:48.560
No big deal. That's low motivation.

63
00:03:48.860 --> 00:03:53.740
They're not in pain. But if they say, I'll
probably lose it to the bank.

64
00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:57.460
Or I honestly can't keep dealing with this
anymore.

65
00:03:57.880 --> 00:03:59.240
That's high motivation.

66
00:03:59.700 --> 00:04:01.520
That's someone who needs to move.

67
00:04:02.260 --> 00:04:08.620
And before you hand this lead off, you
absolutely need to know who actually makes the

68
00:04:08.620 --> 00:04:13.100
call. Ask them. Is there anyone else
involved in making this decision?

69
00:04:13.620 --> 00:04:16.280
A spouse, a sibling, an attorney?

70
00:04:16.280 --> 00:04:21.400
And if we were to present an offer, who
would need to sign off on it?

71
00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:25.220
And what would that conversation look like
on their end?

72
00:04:25.520 --> 00:04:30.720
You need these answers because nothing kills
a deal faster than spending weeks working

73
00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:33.200
with someone who can't actually say yes.

74
00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:38.740
If there's a spouse who needs to be on board,
you need to know that now, not after the

75
00:04:38.740 --> 00:04:42.040
acquisition team has spent hours putting an
offer together.

76
00:04:43.020 --> 00:04:48.280
So that's discovery. You've gone past the
basics and found what's really driving this

77
00:04:48.280 --> 00:04:54.020
seller. The real motivation, the money
pressure, the urgency, and who actually signs.

78
00:04:54.520 --> 00:04:56.320
But knowing the story isn't enough.

79
00:04:56.320 --> 00:05:02.820
Next, we'll talk about one of the most critical
moments in the entire pipeline, handing

80
00:05:02.820 --> 00:05:07.440
this lead to the acquisition team without
dropping any of it.

81
00:05:07.760 --> 00:05:10.860
Because bad handoffs kill deals that should
have closed.

82
00:05:11.560 --> 00:05:12.240
I'll see you there.
